  <mainDescription>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Patterns__Cloud&quot; name=&quot;XE_Patterns__Cloud&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The availability of large network bandwidths along with inexpensive computing and storage has resulted in the creation&#xD;
    of the Cloud Computing concept. A &quot;cloud&quot; of resources&amp;nbsp;is viewed as a single service provided, similar to the&#xD;
    electric utility company that provides electricity. The services dynamically provided to users of the cloud are&#xD;
    computing and storage.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Problem Description&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Flexibility, expandability, and availability are all factors that the cloud computing pattern addresses. Companies have&#xD;
    a need for quick and easy access to services, for these services to be quickly provisioned and expanded as needed, and&#xD;
    for the costs to be based upon the level of service used.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Applicable Context&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Used where costs, flexibility&amp;nbsp;and expandability of shared resources is needed. Using a cloud to provide the&#xD;
    necessary services brings down costs, increases flexibility and expandability.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Pattern Constraints&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Cloud computing requires a certain level of required resources and services in order to be cost effective. Security&#xD;
    issues must be address, since sensitive information and services are often exposed to the Internet. Governance,&#xD;
    support,&amp;nbsp;and availability issues also required attention for this approach to be acceptable.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Pattern Solution&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The solution provided by cloud computing has a number of characteristics:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Self-service&lt;/strong> - the consumer provisions computing capabilities and services as needed. Such things&#xD;
        as&amp;nbsp;computing resources&amp;nbsp;and storage is automatically made available as needed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Network Access&lt;/strong> - services are available over the network and provided to multiple platforms (e.g.,&#xD;
        mobile phones, tablets, laptops, and workstations).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Resource Pooling&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;computing resources and other services&amp;nbsp;are pooled. They&amp;nbsp;serve&#xD;
        multiple consumers resources dynamically assigned and reassigned on-demand.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Scalable&lt;/strong> - services and resources are dynamically provisioned and released, generally&#xD;
        automatically, to scale with demand.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Measured&lt;/strong> - metrics support the control and optimization of&amp;nbsp;resource. Resource usage can be&#xD;
        monitored, controlled, and reported. The cost is based upon this measured usage.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Cloud Computing - the cloud as a service&quot; src=&quot;./resources/Arch-Pattern-cloud.png&quot; width=&quot;338&quot;&#xD;
    height=&quot;237&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Cloud computing is&amp;nbsp;the delivery of flexible and dynamically allocated&amp;nbsp;services, typically&amp;nbsp;over the&#xD;
    Internet. Companies view the cloud as (dynamically) provisioned services, which can be viewed as a utility&amp;nbsp;similar&#xD;
    to electricity or a telephone services. These&amp;nbsp;services are used by the company as required, with the costs&#xD;
    reflecting this usage.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    There are two basic patterns for the provisioning and usage of the cloud, plus a combination:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Private Cloud -&lt;/strong> created within the corporate data center and provides services over the Intranet.&#xD;
        It provides the versatility of a&amp;nbsp;cloud,&amp;nbsp;but retains corporate management, control and security.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Public Cloud&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- a third-party provider delivers the cloud services to the public over the&#xD;
        Internet. The characteristics of a public cloud&amp;nbsp; are:&amp;nbsp;services are sold on-demand (typically by the&#xD;
        minute or the hour);&amp;nbsp;services are&amp;nbsp;highly flexible (resources are added or subtracted on-demand).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Hybrid Cloud&lt;/strong> - a combination of public and on-premises private cloud. This approach requires a lot&#xD;
        of synchronization and coordination between the public portion and the private portion. Mission-critical&#xD;
        applications and sensitive data remains in-house on the private cloud, while large or unpredictable workloads use&#xD;
        the public cloud.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The definition of cloud computing has changed over time, but it has always been categorized into four broad areas based&#xD;
    upon the services provided:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Infrastructure as a service (IaaS)&lt;/strong> - server and/or storage services (e.g., migration&#xD;
        of&amp;nbsp;applications/data to a virtual machine (VM)).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Platform as a service (PaaS)&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;software development and other similar services (e.g., Java or&#xD;
        Perl application development, and typically the hosting as well).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Software as service (SaaS)&lt;/strong> - application level services (e.g., office tools).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;span id=&quot;Unified_Communications_as_a_Service&quot; class=&quot;mw-headline&quot;>&lt;strong>Unified Communications as a Service&#xD;
        (UCaaS)&lt;/strong> - multi-platform communications services (e.g., IP telephony, unified messaging, video&#xD;
        conferencing).&lt;/span>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Related Patterns&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Cloud computing is a type of grid computing that evolved to address QoS (Quality of Service) and reliability problems.&#xD;
    Related patterns are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Grid Computing&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- a&amp;nbsp;type of distributed / parallel computing where a virtual super&#xD;
        computer provides computing services. It is composed of a cluster of&amp;nbsp;loosely coupled (networked) computers&#xD;
        providing the services needed to perform very large tasks.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Mainframe Computer&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- powerful central computers used by large organizations for critical and&#xD;
        centralized applications. Bulk data processing is typically done, such as&amp;nbsp;financial transaction processing.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Utility Computing&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- computing resources, such as computation and storage, are packaged and&#xD;
        provided as a metered services, similar to cloud computing, but simpler since the set of service is very limited.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Peer-to-Peer&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- a distributed network architecture in which individual nodes (peers) in the&#xD;
        network are both suppliers and consumers of services and resources. A variation of the centralized client-server&#xD;
        model where client nodes request access to resources provided by central servers.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
